SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="B">    

Saturday, a U.S. Air Force A-10 Thunderbolt II jet crashed into a
working-class neighborhood in the central West German city of
Remscheid killing six people and severely injuring seven.  Authorities
believe the accident will further erode the already sinking public
support for national defense programs.  West Germany, a staunch NATO
ally, is on the front lines of the East-West struggle.  Even before
this fatal crash, 12 major military aircraft accidents had killed 95
people this year alone in Germany's crowded skies, including 70 deaths
resulting from the crash at an air show at the U.S. base in Ramstein
in August.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d14"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP881222-0126"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="B">    

Today a U.S. Air Force A-10 attack jet crashed in Britain.  The pilot
ejected but his status is unknown.  This accident came two-weeks to
the day after an A-10 crashed in Remscheid, Germany killing five and
injuring dozens while another crashed in Tracey, Arizona, without
fatalities.  With more than 1.75 million flight hours, the A-10 is
statistically the safest fighter in the U.S. inventory.  It
experiences an accident rate of less than 4 Class A mishaps per
100,000 flying hours.  A Class A mishap is one in which there is
either a fatality or damage to an aircraft exceeding $500,000.</SUM>

<SUM
